article.headline: McWilliams-Franklin hits winning shot
article.linkText: Sun get unlikely help, beat Monarchs in final seconds
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- The key pick that opened the lane for
Connecticut's Taj McWilliams-Franklin in the final seconds came
from an unlikely source.

Sacramento post players DeMya Walker and Yolanda Griffith
collided in the paint and McWilliams-Franklin made a running layup
with 3.3 seconds left to give the Sun a 69-67 victory over the
Monarchs on Friday night.

She was grateful for the help, no matter who set it.

"DeMya set a pick on Yo and I had a layup,"
McWilliams-Franklin said.

The winning play was nearly identical to McWilliams-Franklin's
buzzer-beater in Connecticut's 65-63 win over Washington on June
24.

The Sun (8-8) rallied from a 16-point deficit late in the first
half by stepping up their defense and outrebounding the much taller
Monarchs 20-11 in the second half. McWilliams-Franklin is the Sun's
tallest starter at 6-foot-2.

Sacramento's Griffith, Tangela Smith and DeMya Walker are all
6-4.

"They're big with long arms, like trees," McWilliams-Franklin
said. "They like to run, we like to run, but I think our post can
absorb the contact better than they can. We just fight through and
run the play. I think that helps us because it wore them down."

Nykesha Sales led Connecticut with 22 points, while Shannon
Johnson had 14 and McWilliams-Franklin finished with 12. The
Connecticut starters accounted for all but one of the Sun's 40
rebounds -- Katie Douglas and Brooke Wyckoff each had nine.
McWilliams-Franklin had five of Connecticut's nine blocked shots.

"We played as a team tonight," Wyckoff said. "We were making
that extra pass and we gave each other a lot of help."

Griffith led Sacramento (7-9) with 15 points and had 10 of the
Monarchs' 30 rebounds. Tangela Smith added 14.

"Our defense broke down," Sacramento coach Maura McHugh said.
"Our rebounding was not there and we were missing shots."

Connecticut took its first lead at 54-53 with 10:35 left on an
inside basket by McWilliams-Franklin. Six minutes later she made
another layup for a 63-59 lead.

The teams traded baskets down the stretch until the Monarchs
pulled even at 67-all on Ticha Penicheiro's 3-pointer with 1:21
left.

After a Connecticut timeout, Sales inbounded to
McWilliams-Franklin at the top of the key. She spun right, found an
open lane and laid in the winning basket. It was similar to the
winning play at Washington when McWilliams-Franklin took the ball
at the foul line.

"It was a higher version of it," Sun coach Mike Thibault said.
"You have to help out on the other people because if you let
(Sales) get the handoff she's going to the basket."

Griffith had six points in a 14-0 run midway through the first
half to propel the Monarchs to a 30-16 lead with 7:30 left. After a
jumper by the Sun's Wyckoff, the Monarchs answered with four more
points to go up 34-18, their largest lead of the half.

Wyckoff helped Connecticut climb back within six points over the
next five minutes. The 6-1 forward pulled down several key rebounds
and scored five points in a 14-4 run to cut Sacramento's lead to
38-32. Edna Campbell countered with a 3-pointer for the Monarchs
and Kara Lawson hit a free throw to give Sacramento a 42-32
halftime lead.

"In the second half we just came out with the will to win,"
Johnson, who had seven of her eight assists in the second half.
"The post led us because we knew it was going to be an inside
game. We just tried to help them as much as we could."
